body:
# MongoDB Schema Validation

MongoDB validators let you keep a flexible document model without giving up server-side guarantees. Use validators when application-level checks are not enough or when multiple services write to the same collection.

## Create a Collection with `$jsonSchema`

```javascript
db.createCollection("users", {
  validator: {
    $jsonSchema: {
      bsonType: "object",
      required: ["email", "role"],
      properties: {
        email: { bsonType: "string", pattern: "@" },
        role: { enum: ["admin", "member"] },
        profile: {
          bsonType: "object",
          properties: {
            displayName: { bsonType: "string" }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  },
  validationAction: "error",
  validationLevel: "strict"
});
```

## Update an Existing Collection

```javascript
db.runCommand({
  collMod: "users",
  validator: {
    $jsonSchema: {
      bsonType: "object",
      required: ["email"]
    }
  },
  validationAction: "warn",
  validationLevel: "moderate"
});
```

`validationAction: "error"` rejects invalid writes. `validationAction: "warn"` records the violation but allows the write, which is useful during cleanup. `validationLevel: "strict"` applies validation to all inserts and updates, while `moderate` is a softer option for collections that already contain legacy invalid documents.

Pair validation with [[mongodb/crud]] so writes fail early and consistently, and revisit [[mongodb/indexes]] when validators reveal the collection is serving more than one access pattern or entity shape.
